Here is the cleaned-up text:

To edit a model, open it and click Edit Model from the Model Toolbar. If you see a banner indicating that the dataset has changed since the model was created, select Review model settings using the latest data.

Change the model’s general settings in the right side panel. Use the table to select which variables to include in your model. Select at least 2, and no more than 49, variables.

The row with the lock icon indicates the model’s outcome variable, or target. It’s automatically included in the model and can’t be deselected.

Importance or Correlation

Einstein shows metrics to help you decide which variables to include. Correlation shows the strength of association between the variable and the outcome, and importance shows how much the model uses the variable when predicting the outcome.

To choose what you want to see, use the column’s dropdown menu. Importance indicates the degree by which the model chooses to use the variable when predicting the outcome. The higher the importance, the greater the impact.

When importance and correlation are different, best practice is to consider importance. If a variable has little or no importance or correlation, consider deselecting it to improve the model.

To configure settings for an individual variable, select it in the table and use the right panel. For each variable, Einstein uses up to 100 values.

Configure Number Variables
Configure Text Variables
Configure Date Variables

TAB DESCRIPTION
Alert Identifies possible issues detected in the data, such as outliers or duplicates.
Settings Analyze for bias—select to subject the text variable to bias detection.
Transform Use transforms in the variable’s settings to improve data for analysis.
Buckets Choose a bucketing method with the Bucket Values By dropdown.

To group or bucket values as other, deselect them and choose Group deselected values in “Other.” To filter out values, deselect them and choose Exclude deselected values in the dropdown.

Histogram Chart displays distribution of the values by occurrences.

Click Update Model. Optionally, add notes to describe the new version, then click Update.

You can edit general settings for a model. View the CRM Analytics dataset and select the algorithm and validation type. Model training is faster with smart sampling.

Einstein Discovery analyzes the data and creates a new version of the model.
